{"paragraphs":[{"cues":[{"time":0,"text":"Well we all know the World Wide Web"},{"time":2000,"text":"has absolutely transformed publishing, broadcasting,"},{"time":6000,"text":"commerce and social connectivity,"},{"time":8000,"text":"but where did it all come from?"},{"time":10000,"text":"And I'll quote three people:"},{"time":12000,"text":"Vannevar Bush, Doug Engelbart and Tim Berners-Lee."},{"time":15000,"text":"So let's just run through these guys."}]},{"cues":[{"time":17000,"text":"This is Vannevar Bush."},{"time":19000,"text":"Vannevar Bush was the U.S. government's chief scientific adviser during the war."},{"time":22000,"text":"And in 1945,"},{"time":24000,"text":"he published an article in a magazine called Atlantic Monthly."},{"time":27000,"text":"And the article was called \"As We May Think.\""},{"time":30000,"text":"And what Vannevar Bush was saying"},{"time":32000,"text":"was the way we use information is broken."},{"time":35000,"text":"We don't work in terms of libraries"},{"time":38000,"text":"and catalog systems and so forth."},{"time":40000,"text":"The brain works by association."},{"time":42000,"text":"With one item in its thought, it snaps instantly to the next item."},{"time":45000,"text":"And the way information is structured"},{"time":47000,"text":"is totally incapable of keeping up with this process."}]},{"cues":[{"time":50000,"text":"And so he suggested a machine,"},{"time":52000,"text":"and he called it the memex."},{"time":54000,"text":"And the memex would link information,"},{"time":56000,"text":"one piece of information to a related piece of information and so forth."},{"time":59000,"text":"Now this was in 1945."},{"time":61000,"text":"A computer in those days"},{"time":63000,"text":"was something the secret services used to use for code breaking."},{"time":66000,"text":"And nobody knew anything about it."},{"time":68000,"text":"So this was before the computer was invented."},{"time":70000,"text":"And he proposed this machine called the memex."},{"time":72000,"text":"And he had a platform where you linked information to other information,"},{"time":75000,"text":"and then you could call it up at will."}]},{"cues":[{"time":77000,"text":"So spinning forward,"},{"time":79000,"text":"one of the guys who read this article was a guy called Doug Engelbart,"},{"time":81000,"text":"and he was a U.S. Air Force officer."},{"time":83000,"text":"And he was reading it in their library in the Far East."},{"time":86000,"text":"And he was so inspired by this article,"},{"time":88000,"text":"it kind of directed the rest of his life."},{"time":90000,"text":"And by the mid-60s, he was able to put this into action"},{"time":93000,"text":"when he worked at the Stanford Research Lab in California."},{"time":97000,"text":"He built a system."},{"time":99000,"text":"The system was designed to augment human intelligence, it was called."},{"time":102000,"text":"And in a premonition of today's world"},{"time":105000,"text":"of cloud computing and softwares of service,"},{"time":107000,"text":"his system was called NLS"},{"time":109000,"text":"for oN-Line System."}]},{"cues":[{"time":111000,"text":"And this is Doug Engelbart."},{"time":113000,"text":"He was giving a presentation at the Fall Joint Computer Conference"},{"time":116000,"text":"in 1968."},{"time":119000,"text":"What he showed --"},{"time":121000,"text":"he sat on a stage like this, and he demonstrated this system."},{"time":124000,"text":"He had his head mic like I've got."},{"time":126000,"text":"And he works this system."},{"time":128000,"text":"And you can see, he's working between documents"},{"time":130000,"text":"and graphics and so forth."},{"time":132000,"text":"And he's driving it all"},{"time":134000,"text":"with this platform here,"},{"time":136000,"text":"with a five-finger keyboard"},{"time":138000,"text":"and the world's first computer mouse,"},{"time":140000,"text":"which he specially designed in order to do this system."},{"time":142000,"text":"So this is where the mouse came from as well."}]},{"cues":[{"time":144000,"text":"So this is Doug Engelbart."},{"time":146000,"text":"The trouble with Doug Engelbart's system"},{"time":148000,"text":"was that the computers in those days cost several million pounds."},{"time":151000,"text":"So for a personal computer,"},{"time":153000,"text":"a few million pounds was like having a personal jet plane;"},{"time":155000,"text":"it wasn't really very practical."}]},{"cues":[{"time":157000,"text":"But spin on to the 80s"},{"time":159000,"text":"when personal computers did arrive,"},{"time":161000,"text":"then there was room for this kind of system on personal computers."},{"time":163000,"text":"And my company, OWL"},{"time":165000,"text":"built a system called Guide for the Apple Macintosh."},{"time":168000,"text":"And we delivered the world's first hypertext system."},{"time":172000,"text":"And this began to get a head of steam."},{"time":174000,"text":"Apple introduced a thing called HyperCard,"},{"time":176000,"text":"and they made a bit of a fuss about it."},{"time":178000,"text":"They had a 12-page supplement in the Wall Street Journal the day it launched."},{"time":181000,"text":"The magazines started to cover it."},{"time":183000,"text":"Byte magazine and Communications at the ACM"},{"time":185000,"text":"had special issues covering hypertext."},{"time":187000,"text":"We developed a PC version of this product"},{"time":189000,"text":"as well as the Macintosh version."},{"time":191000,"text":"And our PC version became quite mature."}]},{"cues":[{"time":194000,"text":"These are some examples of this system in action in the late 80s."},{"time":198000,"text":"You were able to deliver documents, were able to do it over networks."},{"time":201000,"text":"We developed a system such"},{"time":203000,"text":"that it had a markup language based on html."},{"time":205000,"text":"We called it hml: hypertext markup language."},{"time":208000,"text":"And the system was capable of doing"},{"time":210000,"text":"very, very large documentation systems over computer networks."}]},{"cues":[{"time":214000,"text":"So I took this system to a trade show in Versailles near Paris"},{"time":217000,"text":"in late November 1990."},{"time":220000,"text":"And I was approached by a nice young man called Tim Berners-Lee"},{"time":222000,"text":"who said, \"Are you Ian Ritchie?\" and I said, \"Yeah.\""},{"time":224000,"text":"And he said, \"I need to talk to you.\""},{"time":226000,"text":"And he told me about his proposed system called the World Wide Web."},{"time":229000,"text":"And I thought, well, that's got a pretentious name,"},{"time":232000,"text":"especially since the whole system ran on his computer in his office."},{"time":235000,"text":"But he was completely convinced that his World Wide Web"},{"time":238000,"text":"would take over the world one day."},{"time":240000,"text":"And he tried to persuade me to write the browser for it,"},{"time":242000,"text":"because his system didn't have any graphics or fonts or layout or anything;"},{"time":245000,"text":"it was just plain text."},{"time":247000,"text":"I thought, well, you know, interesting,"},{"time":250000,"text":"but a guy from CERN, he's not going to do this."},{"time":252000,"text":"So we didn't do it."}]},{"cues":[{"time":254000,"text":"In the next couple of years,"},{"time":256000,"text":"the hypertext community didn't recognize him either."},{"time":258000,"text":"In 1992, his paper was rejected for the Hypertext Conference."},{"time":261000,"text":"In 1993,"},{"time":264000,"text":"there was a table at the conference in Seattle,"},{"time":266000,"text":"and a guy called Marc Andreessen"},{"time":268000,"text":"was demonstrating his little browser for the World Wide Web."},{"time":271000,"text":"And I saw it, and I thought, yep, that's it."},{"time":273000,"text":"And the very next year, in 1994, we had the conference here in Edinburgh,"},{"time":276000,"text":"and I had no opposition in having Tim Berners-Lee as the keynote speaker."}]},{"cues":[{"time":280000,"text":"So that puts me in pretty illustrious company."},{"time":282000,"text":"There was a guy called Dick Rowe"},{"time":284000,"text":"who was at Decca Records and turned down The Beatles."},{"time":286000,"text":"There was a guy called Gary Kildall"},{"time":288000,"text":"who went flying his plane"},{"time":290000,"text":"when IBM came looking for an operating system"},{"time":292000,"text":"for the IBM PC,"},{"time":294000,"text":"and he wasn't there, so they went back to see Bill Gates."},{"time":296000,"text":"And the 12 publishers"},{"time":298000,"text":"who turned down J.K. Rowling's Harry Potter, I guess."}]},{"cues":[{"time":301000,"text":"On the other hand, there's Marc Andreessen"},{"time":303000,"text":"who wrote the world's first browser for the World Wide Web."},{"time":305000,"text":"And according to Fortune magazine,"},{"time":307000,"text":"he's worth 700 million dollars."},{"time":309000,"text":"But is he happy?"}]},{"cues":[{"time":311000,"text":"(Laughter)"}]},{"cues":[{"time":313000,"text":"(Applause)"}]}]}